You have to think about async code differently than you think about synchronous code. In PHP you might write:<p><pre><code>  $data = getData();
</code></pre>
And people want to substitute the return for a callback in js.<p><pre><code>  getData(function(data) {
    // Do something with data.
  });
</code></pre>
That indeed does lead to callback mess. But when you are coding in js you rarely should use anonymous functions. I mostly just use them when I might want to perform recursion.  Going back to my example, I would write the operation as an object like so:<p><pre><code>  var SomeObject = {
    start: function() {
      getData(dataGot);
    },

    dataGot: function(data) {

    }
  };
</code></pre>
JavaScript is an object-oriented languages; use objects! They make async painless.
